'''Aruth Wartan''' (or ''Haruth Vartan'', {{lang-hy|Հարութ Վարդան}}, 23 June 1880 – 14 April 1945) was a German [[film actor]] of [[Armenians|Armenian]] origin<ref>[http://golosarmenii.am/article/77293/nemeckij-kinoakter-arut-vartan НЕМЕЦКИЙ КИНОАКТЕР АРУТ ВАРТАН, by [[Artsvi Bakhchinyan]], Voice of Armenia, 2019 (in Russian)]</ref> who appeared in around ninety films during his career, generally in supporting roles.

Born Arutjun Wartanian in [[Nakhichevansky Uyezd|Nakhichevan]] in of the [[Russian Empire]], he was of [[Armenian people|Armenian]] heritage. He graduated from high school in 1898 in [[Tbilisi]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], and then briefly studied medicine in [[Kharkov]] (now in [[Ukraine]]). Around the turn of the century he briefly lived in Japan before relocating to [[St. Petersburg]]. During the [[Revolution of 1905]] he moved to [[Saxony]] in Germany and studied at the [[Freiberg University of Mining and Technology]]. He also worked in Chile and Bolivia before returning to Germany and working as a [[mining engineer]] then moving into acting and performing on the stage and screen (since 1916)<ref>[http://www.cyranos.ch/smwart-d.htm Aruth Wartan]</ref>.

During the early years he often appeared in leading roles, but as time passed he increasing switched to character roles. In the [[Nazi era]] he played small roles, particularly Russians, in propaganda films such as ''[[Attack on Baku]]'' (1942).<ref>Giesen p.187</ref> He died of stroke in the last weeks of the Second World War.

